Mosque in Temecula wins approval of the planning committee 
The construction of a mosque in Temecula found after five hours, often heated public hearing the unanimous approval by the local planning committee. 
Critics accused the project to promote both terrorism and traffic jams. 
But, according to a statement from the Commission on Wednesday evening, the new center of religion is in line with the local rules and will be an aesthetic catch. 
"The project is supported by many good people - of Christians, Jews, Bahais, and many others," Hadi Nael, chairman of the Islamic Centre of Temecula Valley, said on Thursday morning. 
"As Americans that makes me proud." 
"It shows that there is justice." 
"There are only a few opponents," he added. 
"They are just very loud." 
"In this valley wonderful people live." 
The sitting began at 18: 00 and the discussions for and against the building of the centre lasted until almost midnight, and the voices on both sides, according to the Press Enterprise fairly evenly distributed. 
The debate was held on the website of the newspaper. 
"There is no America more," a comment was. 
"It is a different planet of the apes, and the Statue of Liberty is dead in the sand." 
"America is at the end." 
Planned Islamic centres have led in other parts of the country, to protest, for example near Ground Zero, the scene of the attacks on the City of New York on 11 September 2001. 
In the Temecula Valley Imam Mahmoud Harmoush has called for violence. 
His community with some 135 families live for years peacefully in River Side County, but they wanted a larger and better places, as the camp, which they had hired, along with a manufacturer for water filtration plants. 
The new, approximately 2,300 m2 large mosque in the Mediterranean style is to have two minarets and approximately 13m high. 
They should arise on the approximately 17.500 m2 large piece of land in the Nicolas Road near the Chaparral High School. 
Opponents the city council could still lodge an objection to the project. 
